# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: firecracker-microvm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:firecracker-microvm/amazon-web-services] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] The term "virtualization" was coined in the 1960s to refer to a virtual machine (sometimes called "pseudo machine"), a term which itself dates from the experimental IBM M44/44X system.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] The creation and management of virtual machines has also been called "platform virtualization", or "server virtualization", more recently.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] Platform virtualization is performed on a given hardware platform by *host* software (a *control program*), which creates a simulated computer environment, a *virtual machine* (VM), for its *guest* software.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] The guest software is not limited to user applications; many hosts allow the execution of complete operating systems.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] The guest software executes as if it were running directly on the physical hardware, with several notable caveats.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] Access to physical system resources (such as the network access, display, keyboard, and disk storage) is generally managed at a more restrictive level than the *host* processor and system-memory.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] Guests are often restricted from accessing specific peripheral devices, or may be limited to a subset of the device's native capabilities, depending on the hardware access policy implemented by the virtualization host.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] Virtualization often exacts performance penalties, both in resources required to run the hypervisor and in reduced performance on the virtual machine compared to running native on the physical machine.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] However, when multiple VMs are concurrently running on the same physical host, each VM may exhibit varying and unstable performance which highly depends on the workload imposed on the system by other VMs.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] This issue can be addressed by appropriate installation techniques for temporal isolation among virtual machines.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] There are several approaches to platform virtualization.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] In full virtualization, the virtual machine simulates enough hardware to allow an unmodified "guest" OS designed for the same instruction set to be run in isolation.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] This approach was pioneered in 1966 with the IBM CP-40 and CP-67, predecessors of the VM family.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] In paravirtualization, the virtual machine does not necessarily simulate hardware, but instead (or in addition) offers a special API that can only be used by modifying the "guest" OS.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] For this to be possible, the "guest" OS's source code must be available.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] If the source code is available, it is sufficient to replace sensitive instructions with calls to VMM APIs (e.g.: "cli" with "vm_handle_cli()"), then re-compile the OS and use the new binaries.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] This system call to the hypervisor is called a "hypercall" in TRANGO and Xen; it is implemented via a DIAG ("diagnose") hardware instruction in IBM's CMS under VM (which was the origin of the term *hypervisor*)..
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] In hardware-assisted virtualization, the hardware provides architectural support that facilitates building a virtual machine monitor and allows guest OSs to be run in isolation.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] This can be used to assist either full virtualization or paravirtualization.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization was first introduced on the IBM 308X processors in 1980, with the Start Interpretive Execution (SIE) instruction.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] In 2005 and 2006, Intel and AMD developed additional hardware to support virtualization ran on their platforms.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] Sun Microsystems (now Oracle Corporation) added similar features in their UltraSPARC T-Series processors in 2005.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] In 2006, first-generation 32- and 64-bit x86 hardware support was found to rarely offer performance advantages over software virtualization.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] In operating-system-level virtualization, a physical server is virtualized at the operating system level, enabling multiple isolated and secure virtualized servers to run on a single physical server.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] The "guest" operating system environments share the same running instance of the operating system as the host system.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] Thus, the same operating system kernel is also used to implement the "guest" environments, and applications running in a given "guest" environment view it as a stand-alone system.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] A disaster recovery (DR) plan is often considered good practice for a hardware virtualization platform.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] DR of a virtualization environment can ensure high rate of availability during a wide range of situations that disrupt normal business operations.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] In situations where continued operations of hardware virtualization platforms is important, a disaster recovery plan can ensure hardware performance and maintenance requirements are met.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] A hardware virtualization disaster recovery plan involves both hardware and software protection by various methods, including those described below.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] This common method can be used to store data offsite, but data recovery can be a difficult and lengthy process.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] Tape backup data is only as good as the latest copy stored.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] Tape backup methods will require a backup device and ongoing storage material.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] The implementation of this method will require control software and storage capacity for application and data file storage replication typically on the same site.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] The data is replicated on a different disk partition or separate disk device and can be a scheduled activity for most servers and is implemented more for database-type applications.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hardware-virtualization] This method ensures the highest level of disaster recovery protection for a hardware virtualization solution, by providing duplicate hardware and software replication in two distinct geographic areas.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] A **hypervisor**, also known as a **virtual machine monitor** (**VMM**), is a type of computer software, firmware or hardware that creates and runs virtual machines.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] A computer on which a hypervisor runs one or more virtual machines is called a *host machine* or *virtualization server*, and each virtual machine is called a *guest machine*.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] The hypervisor presents the guest operating systems with a virtual operating platform and manages the execution of the guest operating systems.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Unlike an emulator, the guest executes most instructions on the native hardware.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Multiple instances of a variety of operating systems may share the virtualized hardware resources: for example, Linux, Windows, and macOS instances can all run on a single physical x86 machine.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] This contrasts with operating system-level virtualization, where all instances (usually called *containers*) must share a single kernel, though the guest operating systems can differ in user space, such as different Linux distributions with the same kernel.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] The term *hypervisor* is a variant of *supervisor*, a traditional term for the kernel of an operating system: the hypervisor is the supervisor of the supervisors, with *hyper-* used as a stronger variant of *super-*.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] The term dates to circa 1970; IBM coined it for software that ran OS/360 and the 7090 emulator concurrently on the 360/65 and later used it for the DIAG handler of CP-67.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] In the earlier CP/CMS (1967) system, the term *Control Program* was used instead.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Some literature, especially in microkernel contexts, makes a distinction between *hypervisor* and *virtual machine monitor* (*VMM*).
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] There, both components form the overall *virtualization stack* of a certain system.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] *Hypervisor* refers to kernel-space functionality and VMM to user-space functionality.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Specifically in these contexts, a *hypervisor* is a microkernel implementing virtualization infrastructure that must run in kernel-space for technical reasons, such as Intel VMX.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Microkernels implementing virtualization mechanisms are also referred to as *microhypervisor*.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Applying this terminology to Linux, KVM is a *hypervisor* and QEMU or Cloud Hypervisor are VMMs utilizing KVM as hypervisor.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] In his 1973 thesis *Architectural Principles for Virtual Computer Systems*, Robert P.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] These hypervisors run directly on the host's hardware to control the hardware and to manage guest operating systems.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] The first hypervisors, which IBM developed in the 1960s, were native hypervisors.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] These hypervisors run on a conventional operating system (OS) just as other computer programs do.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Type-2 hypervisors abstract guest operating systems from the host operating system, effectively creating an isolated system that can be interacted with by the host.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] The distinction between these two types is not always clear.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] For instance, KVM and bhyve are kernel modules that effectively convert the host operating system to a type-1 hypervisor.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] The first hypervisors providing full virtualization were the test tool SIMMON and the one-off IBM CP-40 research system, which began production use in January 1967 and became the first version of the IBM CP/CMS operating system.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] CP-40 ran on a S/360-40 modified at the Cambridge Scientific Center to support dynamic address translation, a feature that enabled virtualization.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Prior to this time, computer hardware had only been virtualized to the extent to allow multiple user applications to run concurrently, such as in CTSS and IBM M44/44X.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] With CP-40, the hardware's *supervisor state* was virtualized as well, allowing multiple operating systems to run concurrently in separate virtual machine contexts.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Programmers soon implemented CP-40 (as CP-67) for the IBM System/360-67, the first production computer system capable of full virtualization.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] IBM shipped this machine in 1966; it included page-translation-table hardware for virtual memory and other techniques that allowed a full virtualization of all kernel tasks, including I/O and interrupt handling.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] (The "official" operating system, the ill-fated TSS/360, did not employ full virtualization.) Both CP-40 and CP-67 began production use in 1967.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] CP/CMS was available to IBM customers from 1968 to early 1970s, in source code form without support.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] CP/CMS formed part of IBM's attempt to build robust time-sharing systems for its mainframe computers.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] By running multiple operating systems concurrently, the hypervisor increased system robustness and stability: Even if one operating system crashed, the others would continue working without interruption.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Indeed, this even allowed beta or experimental versions of operating systems‍—‌or even of new hardware‍—‌to be deployed and debugged, without jeopardizing the stable main production system, and without requiring costly additional development systems.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] IBM announced its System/370 series in 1970 without the virtual memory feature needed for virtualization, but added it in the August 1972 Advanced Function announcement.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Virtualization has been featured in all successor systems, such that all modern-day IBM mainframes, including the zSeries line, retain backward compatibility with the 1960s-era IBM S/360 line.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] The 1972 announcement also included VM/370, a reimplementation of CP/CMS for the S/370.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Unlike CP/CMS, IBM provided support for this version (though it was still distributed in source code form for several releases).
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] *VM* stands for *Virtual Machine*, emphasizing that all, not just some, of the hardware interfaces are virtualized.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Both VM and CP/CMS enjoyed early acceptance and rapid development by universities, corporate users, and time-sharing vendors, as well as within IBM.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Users played an active role in ongoing development, anticipating trends seen in modern open source projects.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] However, in a series of disputed and bitter battles, time-sharing lost out to batch processing through IBM political infighting, and VM remained IBM's "other" mainframe operating system for decades, losing to MVS.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] It enjoyed a resurgence of popularity and support from 2000 as the z/VM product, for example as the platform for Linux on IBM Z.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] As mentioned above, the VM control program includes a *hypervisor-call* handler that intercepts DIAG ("Diagnose", opcode x'83') instructions used within a virtual machine.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] This provides fast-path non-virtualized execution of file-system access and other operations (DIAG is a model-dependent privileged instruction, not used in normal programming, and thus is not virtualized.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] It is therefore available for use as a signal to the "host" operating system).
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] When first implemented in CP/CMS release 3.1, this use of DIAG provided an operating system interface that was analogous to the System/360 Supervisor Call instruction (SVC), but that did not require altering or extending the system's virtualization of SVC.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] In 1985 IBM introduced the PR/SM hypervisor to manage logical partitions (LPAR).
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Major Unix vendors, including HP, IBM, SGI, and Sun Microsystems, have been selling virtualized hardware since before 2000.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] These have generally been large, expensive systems (in the multimillion-dollar range at the high end), although virtualization has also been available on some low- and mid-range systems, such as IBM pSeries servers, HP Superdome series machines, and Sun/Oracle SPARC T series CoolThreads servers.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] IBM provides virtualization partition technology known as logical partitioning (LPAR) on System/390, zSeries, pSeries and IBM AS/400 systems.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] For IBM's Power Systems, the POWER Hypervisor (PHYP) is a native (bare-metal) hypervisor in firmware and provides isolation between LPARs.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Processor capacity is provided to LPARs in either a dedicated fashion or on an entitlement basis where unused capacity is harvested and can be re-allocated to busy workloads.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Groups of LPARs can have their processor capacity managed as if they were in a "pool" - IBM refers to this capability as Multiple Shared-Processor Pools (MSPPs) and implements it in servers with the POWER6 processor.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] LPAR and MSPP capacity allocations can be dynamically changed.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Memory is allocated to each LPAR (at LPAR initiation or dynamically) and is address-controlled by the POWER Hypervisor.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] For real-mode addressing by operating systems (AIX, Linux, IBM i), the Power processors (POWER4 onwards) have designed virtualization capabilities where a hardware address-offset is evaluated with the OS address-offset to arrive at the physical memory address.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Input/Output (I/O) adapters can be exclusively "owned" by LPARs or shared by LPARs through an appliance partition known as the Virtual I/O Server (VIOS).
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] HPE provides HP Integrity Virtual Machines (Integrity VM) to host multiple operating systems on their Itanium powered Integrity systems.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Itanium can run HP-UX, Linux, Windows and OpenVMS, and these environments are also supported as virtual servers on HP's Integrity VM platform.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] While it heavily leverages HP-UX, the Integrity VM hypervisor is really a hybrid that runs on bare-metal while guests are executing.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Running normal HP-UX applications on an Integrity VM host is heavily discouraged, because Integrity VM implements its own memory management, scheduling and I/O policies that are tuned for virtual machines and are not as effective for normal applications.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] HPE also provides more rigid partitioning of their Integrity and HP9000 systems by way of VPAR and nPar technology, the former offering shared resource partitioning and the latter offering complete I/O and processing isolation.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] The flexibility of virtual server environment (VSE) has given way to its use more frequently in newer deployments.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Wind River "Carrier Grade Linux" also runs on Sun's Hypervisor.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Full virtualization on SPARC processors proved straightforward: since its inception in the mid-1980s Sun deliberately kept the SPARC architecture clean of artifacts that would have impeded virtualization.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Similar trends have occurred with x86/x86-64 server platforms, where open-source projects such as Xen have led virtualization efforts.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] These include hypervisors built on Linux and Solaris kernels as well as custom kernels.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Since these technologies span from large systems down to desktops, they are described in the next section.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] x86 virtualization was introduced in the 1990s, with its emulation being included in Bochs.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Intel and AMD released their first x86 processors with hardware virtualisation in 2005 with Intel VT-x (code-named Vanderpool) and AMD-V (code-named Pacifica).
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] An alternative approach requires modifying the guest operating system to make a system call to the underlying hypervisor, rather than executing machine I/O instructions that the hypervisor simulates.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] This is called paravirtualization in Xen, a "hypercall" in Parallels Workstation, and a "DIAGNOSE code" in IBM VM.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Some microkernels, such as Mach and L4, are flexible enough to allow paravirtualization of guest operating systems.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Embedded hypervisors, targeting embedded systems and certain real-time operating system (RTOS) environments, are designed with different requirements when compared to desktop and enterprise systems, including robustness, security and real-time capabilities.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] The resource-constrained nature of multiple embedded systems, especially battery-powered mobile systems, imposes a further requirement for small memory-size and low overhead.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Finally, in contrast to the ubiquity of the x86 architecture in the PC world, the embedded world uses a wider variety of architectures and less standardized environments.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Support for virtualization requires memory protection (in the form of a memory management unit or at least a memory protection unit) and a distinction between user mode and privileged mode, which rules out most microcontrollers.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] This still leaves x86, MIPS, ARM and PowerPC as widely deployed architectures on medium- to high-end embedded systems.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] As manufacturers of embedded systems usually have the source code to their operating systems, they have less need for full virtualization in this space.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Instead, the performance advantages of paravirtualization make this usually the virtualization technology of choice.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Nevertheless, ARM and MIPS have recently added full virtualization support as an IP option and has included it in their latest high-end processors and architecture versions, such as ARM Cortex-A15 MPCore and ARMv8 EL2.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] Implementation of the concept has allegedly occurred in the SubVirt laboratory rootkit (developed jointly by Microsoft and University of Michigan researchers) as well as in the Blue Pill malware package.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] However, such assertions have been disputed by others who claim that it would be possible to detect the presence of a hypervisor-based rootkit.
[src:firecracker-microvm/hypervisor] In 2009, researchers from Microsoft and North Carolina State University demonstrated a hypervisor-layer anti-rootkit called Hooksafe that can provide generic protection against kernel-mode rootkits.
[src:firecracker-microvm/kernel-based-virtual-machine] KVM was originally designed for x86 processors but has since been ported to z/Architecture, PowerPC, IA-64, and ARM.
[src:firecracker-microvm/kernel-based-virtual-machine] KVM supports hardware-assisted virtualization for a wide variety of guest operating systems including BSD, Solaris, Windows, Haiku, ReactOS, Plan 9, AROS, macOS, and even other Linux systems.
[src:firecracker-microvm/kernel-based-virtual-machine] In addition, Android 2.2, GNU/Hurd (Debian K16), Minix 3.1.2a, Solaris 10 U3 and Darwin 8.0.1, together with other operating systems and some newer versions of these listed, are known to work with certain limitations.
[src:firecracker-microvm/kernel-based-virtual-machine] Additionally, KVM provides paravirtualization support for Linux, OpenBSD, FreeBSD, NetBSD, Plan 9 and Windows guests using the VirtIO API.
[src:firecracker-microvm/kernel-based-virtual-machine] This includes a paravirtual Ethernet card, disk I/O controller, balloon driver, and a VGA graphics interface using SPICE or VMware drivers.
[src:firecracker-microvm/kernel-based-virtual-machine] Avi Kivity began the development of KVM in mid-2006 at Qumranet, a technology startup company that was acquired by Red Hat in 2008.
[src:firecracker-microvm/kernel-based-virtual-machine] KVM surfaced in October 2006 and was merged into the Linux kernel mainline in version 2.6.20, released on 5 February 2007.
[src:firecracker-microvm/kernel-based-virtual-machine] KVM provides device abstraction but no processor emulation.
[src:firecracker-microvm/kernel-based-virtual-machine] Originally, a forked version of QEMU was provided to launch guests and deal with hardware emulation that is not handled by the kernel.
[src:firecracker-microvm/kernel-based-virtual-machine] That support was eventually merged into the upstream project.
[src:firecracker-microvm/kernel-based-virtual-machine] There are now numerous Virtual Machine Monitors (VMMs) which can utilise the KVM interface including kvmtool, crosvm and Firecracker and numerous specialised VMMs built with frameworks such as rust-vmm.
[src:firecracker-microvm/kernel-based-virtual-machine] Internally, KVM uses SeaBIOS as an open source implementation of a 16-bit x86 BIOS.
[src:firecracker-microvm/kernel-based-virtual-machine] KVM has had support for hot swappable vCPUs, dynamic memory management, and Live Migration since February 2007.
[src:firecracker-microvm/kernel-based-virtual-machine] It also reduces the impact that memory write-intensive workloads have on the migration process.
[src:firecracker-microvm/kernel-based-virtual-machine] KVM itself emulates very little hardware, instead deferring to a higher level client application such as QEMU, crosvm, or Firecracker for device emulation.
[src:firecracker-microvm/kernel-based-virtual-machine] The kernel-mode component of KVM is a part of the Linux kernel, itself licensed under GNU General Public License, version 2.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:firecracker-microvm/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] In computing, a **virtual machine** (**VM**) is the virtualization or emulation of a computer system.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are based on computer architectures and provide the functionality of a physical computer.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Their implementations may involve specialized hardware, software, or a combination of the two.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Some virtual machine emulators, such as QEMU and video game console emulators, are designed to also emulate (or "virtually imitate") different system architectures, thus allowing execution of software applications and operating systems written for another CPU or architecture.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] OS-level virtualization allows the resources of a computer to be partitioned via the kernel.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] The terms are not universally interchangeable.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] A 'virtual machine' was originally defined by Popek and Goldberg as "an efficient, isolated duplicate of a real computer machine." Current use includes virtual machines that have no direct correspondence to any real hardware.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] The physical, "real-world" hardware running the VM is generally referred to as the 'host', and the virtual machine emulated on that machine is generally referred to as the 'guest'.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] A host can emulate several guests, each of which can emulate different operating systems and hardware platforms.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] The desire to run multiple operating systems was the initial motive for virtual machines, so as to allow time-sharing among several single-tasking operating systems.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] In some respects, a system virtual machine can be considered a generalization of the concept of virtual memory that historically preceded it.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] IBM's CP/CMS, the first systems to allow full virtualization, implemented time sharing by providing each user with a single-user operating system, the Conversational Monitor System (CMS).
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Unlike virtual memory, a system virtual machine entitled the user to write privileged instructions in their code.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] This approach had certain advantages, such as adding input/output devices not allowed by the standard system.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] As technology evolves virtual memory for purposes of virtualization, new systems of memory overcommitment may be applied to manage memory sharing among multiple virtual machines on one computer operating system.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] It may be possible to share *memory pages* that have identical contents among multiple virtual machines that run on the same physical machine, what may result in mapping them to the same physical page by a technique termed kernel same-page merging (KSM).
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] This is especially useful for read-only pages, such as those holding code segments, which is the case for multiple virtual machines running the same or similar software, software libraries, web servers, middleware components, etc.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] The guest operating systems do not need to be compliant with the host hardware, thus making it possible to run different operating systems on the same computer (e.g., Windows, Linux, or prior versions of an operating system) to support future software.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] The use of virtual machines to support separate guest operating systems is popular in regard to embedded systems.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] A typical use would be to run a real-time operating system simultaneously with a preferred complex operating system, such as Linux or Windows.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Another use would be for novel and unproven software still in the developmental stage, so it runs inside a sandbox.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Virtual machines have other advantages for operating system development and may include improved debugging access and faster reboots.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Multiple VMs running their own guest operating system are frequently engaged for server consolidation.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] A **process virtual machine**, sometimes called an *application virtual machine*, or *Managed Runtime Environment* (MRE), runs as a normal application inside a host OS and supports a single process.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] It is created when that process is started and deleted when it is closed.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Its purpose is to provide a platform-independent programming environment that abstracts away details of the underlying hardware or operating system and allows a program to execute in the same way on any platform.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] A process VM provides a high-level abstraction – that of a high-level programming language (compared to the low-level ISA abstraction of the system VM).
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Process VMs are implemented using an interpreter; performance comparable to compiled programming languages can be achieved by the use of just-in-time compilation.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] This type of VM has become popular with the Java programming language, which is implemented using the Java virtual machine.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Other examples include the Parrot virtual machine and the .NET Framework, which runs on a VM called the Common Language Runtime.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] All of them can serve as an abstraction layer for any computer language.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] A special case of process VMs are systems that abstract over the communication mechanisms of a (potentially heterogeneous) computer cluster.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Such a VM does not consist of a single process, but one process per physical machine in the cluster.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] They are designed to ease the task of programming concurrent applications by letting the programmer focus on algorithms rather than the communication mechanisms provided by the interconnect and the OS.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] They do not hide the fact that communication takes place, and as such do not attempt to present the cluster as a single machine.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Unlike other process VMs, these systems do not provide a specific programming language, but are embedded in an existing language; typically such a system provides bindings for several languages (e.g., C and Fortran).
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Examples are Parallel Virtual Machine (PVM) and Message Passing Interface (MPI).
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Both system virtual machines and process virtual machines date to the 1960s and remain areas of active development.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Significant advances occurred in the implementation of Smalltalk-80, particularly the Deutsch/Schiffmann implementation which pushed just-in-time (JIT) compilation forward as an implementation approach that uses process virtual machine.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Later notable Smalltalk VMs were VisualWorks, the Squeak Virtual Machine, and Strongtalk.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] A related language that produced a lot of virtual machine innovation was the Self programming language, which pioneered adaptive optimization and generational garbage collection.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] These techniques proved commercially successful in 1999 in the HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Other innovations include a register-based virtual machine, to better match the underlying hardware, rather than a stack-based virtual machine, which is a closer match for the programming language; in 1995, this was pioneered by the Dis virtual machine for the Limbo language.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] In full virtualization, the virtual machine simulates enough hardware to allow an unmodified "guest" OS (one designed for the same instruction set) to be run in isolation.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] In hardware-assisted virtualization, the hardware provides architectural support that facilitates building a virtual machine monitor and allows guest OSes to be run in isolation.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Hardware-assisted virtualization was first introduced on the IBM System/370 in 1972, for use with VM/370, the first virtual machine operating system offered by IBM as an official product.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] In 2005 and 2006, Intel and AMD provided additional hardware to support virtualization.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Sun Microsystems (acquired by Oracle Corporation) added similar features in their UltraSPARC T-Series processors in 2005.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Examples of virtualization platforms adapted to such hardware include KVM, VMware Workstation, VMware Fusion, Hyper-V, Windows Virtual PC, Xen, Parallels Desktop for Mac, Oracle VM Server for SPARC, VirtualBox and Parallels Workstation.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] In OS-level virtualization, a physical server is virtualized at the operating system level, enabling multiple isolated and secure virtualized servers to run on a single physical server.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] The pioneer implementation was FreeBSD jails; other examples include Docker, Solaris Containers, OpenVZ, Linux-VServer, LXC, AIX Workload Partitions, Parallels Virtuozzo Containers, and iCore Virtual Accounts.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] A *snapshot* is a state of a virtual machine, and generally its storage devices, at an exact point in time.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] A snapshot enables the virtual machine's state at the time of the snapshot to be restored later, effectively undoing any changes that occurred afterwards.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] This capability is useful as a backup technique, for example, prior to performing a risky operation.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Virtual machines frequently use virtual disks for their storage; in a very simple example, a 10-gigabyte hard disk drive is simulated with a 10-gigabyte flat file.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Any requests by the VM for a location on its physical disk are transparently translated into an operation on the corresponding file.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Once such a translation layer is present, however, it is possible to intercept the operations and send them to different files, depending on various criteria.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Every time a snapshot is taken, a new file is created, and used as an overlay for its predecessors.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] New data is written to the topmost overlay; reading existing data, however, needs the overlay hierarchy to be scanned, resulting in accessing the most recent version.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Thus, the entire stack of snapshots is virtually a single coherent disk; in that sense, creating snapshots works similarly to the incremental backup technique.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Other components of a virtual machine can also be included in a snapshot, such as the contents of its random-access memory (RAM), BIOS settings, or its configuration settings.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] "Save state" feature in video game console emulators is an example of such snapshots.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Restoring a snapshot consists of discarding or disregarding all overlay layers that are added after that snapshot, and directing all new changes to a new overlay.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] The snapshots described above can be moved to another host machine with its own hypervisor; when the VM is temporarily stopped, snapshotted, moved, and then resumed on the new host, this is known as migration.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] If the older snapshots are kept in sync regularly, this operation can be quite fast, and allow the VM to provide uninterrupted service while its prior physical host is, for example, taken down for physical maintenance.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Similar to the migration mechanism described above, failover allows the VM to continue operations if the host fails.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Generally it occurs if the migration has stopped working.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] However, in this case, the VM continues operation from the *last-known* coherent state, rather than the *current* state, based on whatever materials the backup server was last provided with.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Nested virtualization refers to the ability of running a virtual machine within another, having this general concept extendable to an arbitrary depth.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] In other words, nested virtualization refers to running one or more hypervisors inside another hypervisor.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] The nature of a nested guest virtual machine does not need to be homogeneous with its host virtual machine; for example, application virtualization can be deployed within a virtual machine created by using hardware virtualization.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Furthermore, moving already existing virtualized environments into a cloud, following the Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) approach, is much more complicated if the destination IaaS platform does not support nested virtualization.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] The way nested virtualization can be implemented on a particular computer architecture depends on supported hardware-assisted virtualization capabilities.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] If a particular architecture does not provide hardware support required for nested virtualization, various software techniques are employed to enable it.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Over time, more architectures gain required hardware support; for example, since the Haswell microarchitecture (announced in 2013), Intel started to include VMCS shadowing as a technology that accelerates nested virtualization.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are frequently used to isolate applications from one another for security.
[src:firecracker-microvm/virtual-machine] This architectural design (used by Qubes OS, Whonix, KickSecure, and Dangerzone) can prevent the spread of malware from one compromised system (e.g. an email client opening an infected document) to another system (e.g. a password manager).
